ce:section.ce:para:
Additionally, YCDs treatment enhances oilseed rape growth through various physiological indicators (
                        Fig. S9
                     ). YCDs treatment significantly improved the antioxidant enzyme system, including CAT, POD, and SOD, compared to CDs treatment. Specifically, YCDs increased CAT activity in shoots by 311.97 % (0.239 U/mg protein) compared to the control (0.058 U/mg protein) and in roots by 252.89 % (0.373 U/mg protein) compared to the control (0.106 U/mg protein). Total protein (TP) plays a crucial role in maintaining plant life activities. The results indicate that TP concentration in shoots treated with YCDs decreased by 37.17 % (from 17.652 g/L to 11.090 g/L) compared to the control, and 30.85 % (from 7.932 g/L to 5.485 g/L) in roots. This reduction in soluble protein synthesis suggests that YCDs could contribute to conserve surplus energy resources for the synthesis of cold-resistant substances and reduce oxidative stress in oilseed rape. Furthermore, the reduced content of proline (PRO) suggests YCDs improve the plant’s adaptability to cold damage and mitigate oxidative stress [40]. VC (vitamin C), also known as the ascorbic acid, is an important antioxidant in plants that protects oilseed rape cells from low-temperature damage, scavenges free radicals, and reduces cellular damage, and the YCDs treatment could also enhance the level of VC in shoots and roots. These findings indicate that YCDs treatment effectively restores intracellular homeostasis in oilseed rape under cold stress.
